For {= firm =}+ consulting, engineering, advisory, or project-services firms/entities with public energy, power, infrastructure, e-mobility, climate/energy-efficiency, transmission/distribution, electricity-market, or comparable development-infrastructure work, name {= public_claim =}+ concrete public claims per firm/entity. Each public claim should be a named or otherwise bounded in-scope project, engagement, consulting/advisory/verifier/provider credential, relevant registry/accreditation status, award, contract, public project record, technical study/report role, JV/team role, or scoped assignment, not a broad service-line/category capability or generic corporate sustainability status. For each (`firm`, `public_claim`) pair and each of the {= evidence_side =} evidence sides listed below, supply a source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL).

Firm profiles and project pages are often self-asserting; the useful public provenance is whether a concrete claim can also be tied to an independent public record without turning that evidence into a procurement, ranking, compliance, safety, or technical-adequacy conclusion.

The evidence sides of interest, which we refer to as `evidence_side`, are:
- `firm_claim`: a public source where the submitted firm/entity itself is the speaker for the claim through a firm-owned, firm-authored, firm-submitted, or otherwise firm-controlled surface. A report, filing, or portal submission hosted by someone else can count only when the page visibly identifies the submitted firm/entity as the author, submitter, or speaker for that specific claim.
- `independent_record`: an external actor's own public record, not controlled by the submitted firm/entity, with a corroborating, narrowing, dating, credentialing, award, procurement, registry/accreditation, client/funder/project, JV/team/member, or page-backed conflict/limitation posture for the same claim. A public/client/funder-hosted report, filing, or deliverable authored or submitted by the firm can count as `firm_claim` when firm authorship/submission is visible, but that same firm-authored/submitted deliverable is not by itself an `independent_record` merely because someone else hosts it.

Firms/entities ought to be real consulting, engineering, professional-services, project-management, development-advisory, or comparable project-services organizations in the in-scope domains. Pure charger vendors, charging-station maps, product sellers, RFQ portals, contact directories, and app/operator pages do not count unless the page clearly establishes relevant consulting or project-services work. Public claims should be concrete, source-checkable, and domain-bearing; generic phrases such as "energy expertise", "EV experience", "infrastructure capability", "CDP disclosure support", or "energy-efficiency services" are not enough unless they are tied to a named or bounded project, engagement, consulting/advisory/verifier/provider credential, relevant registry/accreditation status, award, contract, report, public project record, technical study, JV/team role, or scoped assignment. SBTi target rows, UN Global Compact participant or Communication on Progress pages, generic annual/sustainability reports, corporate emissions commitments, and broad ESG-program participation are not in-scope public claims merely because the firm is a consultant or infrastructure actor; they count only when the cited page itself ties the status or report to an in-scope consulting/advisory/verifier/provider role or a public project/assignment. The pages should be fully public, accessible, usable, and page-specific enough to evaluate the claim.

Requirements:
- The page must identify the submitted firm/entity, or explicitly identify a JV, consortium, team, or member relationship that binds the submitted firm/entity to the claim.
- The page must identify the same public claim enough to match the submitted `public_claim`, such as the in-scope project, engagement, assignment, consulting/advisory/verifier/provider credential, relevant registry/accreditation status, role, study/report, contract, award, public project record, scoped assignment, or narrower/conflicting public version of it.
- The page should communicate side-appropriate source posture: for `firm_claim`, a firm-owned, firm-authored, firm-submitted, or otherwise firm-controlled public source where the firm is the speaker for the claim, including externally hosted submissions only when visible authorship or submission anchors make that firm-speaker role clear; for `independent_record`, an external actor's own non-firm-controlled public record such as government, donor, funder, client, development-bank, procurement, award, shortlist, issuer/registry/accreditation locator, official project page, external annual/public report, or reputable infrastructure/public-sector reporting. Public hosting of the firm's own report, filing, or deliverable is not enough for `independent_record` unless the external actor's own page text, metadata, notice, registry entry, project page, award/procurement record, or comparable record separately binds the firm to the claim.
- The page should supply a concrete side-appropriate in-scope claim detail. For `firm_claim`, this means the firm's own stated bounded project, consulting/advisory/verifier/provider credential, assignment, JV/team role, technical-study/report role, award, contract, relevant registry/accreditation status, or scoped assignment detail. For `independent_record`, this means an external actor's own public corroboration, narrowing, dating, credentialing, award/contract/procurement detail, registry/accreditation status, client/funder/project or JV/team naming, or page-backed conflict/limitation for the same bounded in-scope claim; arbitrary absence from web search and mere repetition inside a firm-authored/submitted deliverable do not count as independent claim detail.
